= Abstract

In this course, we will begin with a *generalized definition of swing*—not as a musical style, but
as the transformation of the subdivision grid into unequal parts.

From this foundation, we will explore a wide range of rhythmic phenomena and concepts,
including _Groove Balance_ and _Rhythm Entropy/Tension_, _Morphing Rhythms and Bridge Meters_,
_Fractal Rhythms and Irrational Ratios_, _Rhythm Tempering and the Timbre of the Pulse_, _Mirrored
Swings_, and many more.

We will also dive into aspects of psychoacoustics, such as the _range of perception vs. functional
perception_, _Groove Effect - depth of the beat_, …

And yes—even some mathematics: from _Euclidean and Prime Rhythms_ to _Vector Space_ and
_Harmonic_ approaches, and from the contrast between _Absolute and Functional Time_ to the idea
of a _transfer function for rhythm_.

Additionally, we will examine the application of these concepts in Computer and Electronic Music.

Every concept will be anchored in instrumental practice through a series of comprehensive, bodycentered
exercises. The goal is to provide students with practical tools that they can immediately
apply in their performance and improvisation, as well as in their compositional work.
